{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17514151","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17514151"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:19:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:19:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12282"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12282","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12282"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.02,0.84,0.13,0]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4804"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61890"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4804","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4804"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12282"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47336"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"528"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"9598"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7710"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7733"},{"type":"contributions","id":"15460"},{"type":"contributions","id":"19125"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/61890"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 37-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department with haematemesis following a prolonged bout of intense retching and vomiting. He has a history of alcohol misuse but no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He denies any previous episodes of chest or abdominal pain. His stool appearance and consistency are normal and unchanged.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 102/68 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 37.0\u00b0C. Abdominal examination is unremarkable. Digital rectal examination reveals brown stool. His vomit appears to contain fresh bright red blood. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reflux oesophagitis","Peptic ulcer disease","Mallory-Weiss syndrome","Oesophageal varices","Gastritis"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with fresh haematemesis following forceful vomiting, which is characteristic of \u003Cstrong\u003EMallory-Weiss syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E. This condition occurs when intense retching causes a linear mucosal tear at the gastro-oesophageal junction. The association with alcohol use and the absence of preceding pain are typical features. The fresh nature of the blood suggests active bleeding from a mucosal tear rather than altered blood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReflux oesophagitis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with retrosternal burning pain and rarely causes significant haematemesis. When bleeding does occur, it usually presents as coffee-ground vomitus rather than fresh blood. Chronic blood loss may lead to iron deficiency anaemia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeptic ulcer disease\u003C/strong\u003E, while the most common cause of upper gastrointestinal bleeding overall, typically presents with epigastric pain and is associated with NSAID use or \u003Cem\u003EH. pylori \u003C/em\u003Einfection. Patients usually present with coffee-ground vomitus and melaena rather than fresh haematemesis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EOesophageal varices\u003C/strong\u003E can cause massive haematemesis but typically occur in patients with portal hypertension and cirrhosis. Physical examination would usually reveal signs of chronic liver disease such as spider naevi, palmar erythema, or ascites, which are not present in this case. Additionally, the history of intense retching followed by haematemesis is more characteristic of Mallory-Weiss syndrome. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastritis\u003C/strong\u003E typically presents with epigastric discomfort and nausea. When bleeding occurs, it usually manifests as coffee-ground vomitus rather than fresh blood, as the blood has time to be altered by gastric acid.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Mallory-Weiss tears typically present with haematemesis following forceful retching or vomiting","Mallory-Weiss tears account for 4-8% of upper gastrointestinal bleeding cases","The absence of preceding epigastric pain and presence of fresh blood rather than coffee-ground vomitus helps distinguish Mallory-Weiss tears from other causes of upper GI bleeding"],"references":["Kamboj AK, Hoversten P, Leggett CL. Upper Gastrointestinal Bleeding: Etiologies and Management. Mayo Clinic Proceedings. 2019 Apr 1;94(4):697\u2013703. Available at: https://www.mayoclinicproceedings.org/article/S0025-6196(19)30091-6/fulltext","Sverden E, Markar, SR, Agreus L, et al. Acute upper gastrointestinal bleeding. BMJ 2018; 363: k4023. Available at: https://www.bmj.com/content/363/bmj.k4023"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47336"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12282"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"47336","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/47336"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-16T19:56:51+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-16T19:57:40+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4804"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"61890"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://